<div class="notes">
Another neat thing currently in progress: brain simulation.

An important project in brain modelling is the OpenWorm.  This includes a complete simulation of a nematode worm, a tiny, simple, and very well-studied animal.  It has under 1000 cells, including just 302 neurons.  So OpenWorm is creating a complete cell-level model of this worm, allowing for complete simulation of the worm and how it interacts with its environment.  It's still in development, but once complete could act as the base for simulations of larger animals, progressing eventually to humans.
(see http://www.openworm.org)

Interesting fact: the muscle movements work on smoothed particle hydrodynamics, same as those water simulations earlier and the galaxy simulation before that.  It surprised me how versatile this method is.
</div>

